We’ve got an amazing team down here at the ranch, working really hard on days like today! 
This is “work”, in every sense of the word, but it’s also a lifestyle. Working to help those who can’t help themselves, or are voiceless, gives new, spiritual meaning to life and often involves shedding your old skin. Many of us have let go of toxic elements like drugs and alcohol in favor of a slightly less toxic obsession: dogs!

Help us Celebrate Courage’s Anniversary! 

The story of Courage the fighting dog will hit just about every emotion. We rescued Courage after he was saved from an illegal dog fighting ring, where is ears and tongue had been removed. 
Caring for a dog with no tongue is challenging, as they can’t eat or drink initially. We had to feed him through a lactated ringer and by hand, until he learned on his own.
Courage began life scared of everything—people, places and things. During our drive across America, we bonded, setting the stage for a new beginning! 
Today, courage has his own Condo at the ranch and LOVES his handlers and caregivers! He is a testament to forgiveness and dogged determination! 
He’s also become one heck of an office dog and mascot! Courage continues to learn how to integrate with new people and dogs and is one of the most loving, connected dogs we have at the rescue ranch! 
I love me a good second chance tale, and Courage’s is second to none!

Our brave boy!

HUGE NEWS! 

Freedom means so many things to the dogs in our care. For most it means we save them from euthanasia at a public shelter. We give them time to decompress and learn how to be a dog and then when the time is right we find them amazing forever homes where they get to live life to the fullest as a cherished member of a family.

Dogs like Courage, fighting ring dogs, never get that chance. Often they have behavior so unpredictable, after years of abuse, they aren’t stable enough for a normal home environment. They’re often euthanized or if they’re lucky live in a sanctuary type setting. That’s the best outcome most can hope for, a sanctuary…..but we believe in miracles and we’re witnessing one right now! 

Courage after 1100 days in our care (that’s over 3 years if your math is slow) is in a foster home!!!! This isn’t a single dog foster home. He’s living in harmony with multiple dogs and even a few kitties. To say we are overwhelmed and just a little speechless with emotion is an understatement. We have no words and this is something we never saw happening. To overcome what Courage has is a testament to the amazing dog he’s always been. Today is #freedomfriday today we celebrate the courage this incredible dog continues to show us each and every day ❤️

Ladies and gents, the @marleysmutts Rescue Ranch wants YOU!!! 
We are looking for dog walkers, bathers and used-dog advocates! We’ve got nearly 80 certified, pre owned puppies, big dogs and small dogs at the ranch looking for your love! 
The ranch has a great vibe and there are plenty of places nearby to hike, or have a doggy-day-out! 
Please visit the link in my bio or MarleysMutts.org for more info!

There are things in rescue that fill our hearts and fuel our souls. Adoption is one of those things. For a dog like Courage, who we never thought adoption would be an option, miracles sometimes happen. 

Courage the former fighting dog who struggled to trust and find his place after years of abuse is living his very own miracle! He’s officially found the most amazing adoptive home any dog would be proud to have. Through tears we watch as our sweet boy enters the next chapter of his life. 1,223 days in our care, that’s almost 3.5 years and Courage had grown and changed every single one of those days. This dog has taught us that your past doesn’t define your future, it’s never too late to make change and that if you just believe your dreams will come true ❤️

Congratulations Courage your real journey has just begun!!!! We couldn’t think of a more AMAZING way to celebrate #freedomfriday!

The house that Hooch built—painted by the incredible @art_noumenon ! 
I met Nhut Vo while he was incarcerated at Wasco State Prison, bettering himself in our @pawsitivechangeprogram .
I gravitated towards him immediately and we became friends. When Marley died, he surprised me with a 5ft painting of Marley on wooden canvas, which the institution allowed him to create. It proudly hangs at the entrance of our Rescue Ranch. 
Vo was released from prison and has successfully pursued a career in dog training and art. After Hooch passed, @marleysmutts commissioned him to paint the barn in Hooch’s honor. It one of the most beautiful murals I’ve ever seen, memorializing the big, orange bear like only Vo could! 
I am so proud to have had a small role in Vo’s successful trajectory and even more proud to call him a friend. 
Show some love to Vo by following his art and dog training pages here: @redemptiontails.llc @art_noumenon 
🙏🙌🤍💯
Thank you for giving to @marleysmutts and helping us save more dogs like Courage!
